When I told my friend I was going to SF and that Brenda's was on my list, he promptly said something along the lines of be careful and hinted at not wanting me to go anywhere near the area (tenderloin) alone. Aww. Such a cutie! Lol! Thanks... But uh, I've been to all the "icky" parts of LA so I'm good. We did end up going together tho. That might've been his fatty plan all along. Haha. We parked a few blocks away and went for breakfast on a Monday morning, he stared at the floor making sure not to step in sh*t while I looked around at the supposed "bad area." Me thinks it reminds me of when ppl say to watch yourself in DTSA (Downtown Santa Ana for the non SoCal residents) a place where hipsters roam free and the older white folk tend to just run away. Arriving just before ten-ish, there was no wait and still plenty of free tables. We ordered: Sweet Watermelon House Tea-- Fantastic! Not too sweet, which I hate. Watermelon juice is my fav so a watermelon tea was a no brainier and a perfect accompaniment to the dishes we chose. Crawfish Beignets-- Spiced with cayenne, scallions, and cheddar. Wow! Holy moly that's good. A beignet filled with crawfish and cheese that's spiced with cayenne. What's not to love?! Shrimp & Grits-- Sautéed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy. Um, I have no words... Yes, I do! GET THIS NOW!!! F---it's GOOD! The corn has been ground so fine, you'd swear you were eating corn flavored mashed potatoes, no lumps! The kicker here is that they add cheese! F'ing Cheddar Cheese!!! I LOVE CHEESE!!! I'm getting too excited just writing about it. Please order this, you won't be sorry. Grillades & Grits w/Biscuit-- Braised beef cutlets in spicy creole gravy, served with grits & two eggs any style, plus cream biscuit or toast. Those braised beef cutlets were SO tender! And that biscuit was so soft and buttery! I would've tried more of it, but I was already stuffed beyond belief with my own dish ;p Can't wait to go back and have those grits again! Nom Nom Nom *drool*

I'm not sure what to say. I was super excited to try this place, but from the service to the food, it was bad. Yelp raves about this place and I was expecting some delicious soul food brunch fusion on Memorial Day weekend. Before we left the restaurant, I must've called on five different occasions to try to confirm the wait time, but the phone line went unanswered every time. Nevertheless, we made the drive and were ready to wait. I'm really not picky with service, but this was pretty bad. The host was, bluntly, rude. We waited for about 30 minutes, and he asked us if we would be OK with the bar counter by the door. Seeing as it was surrounded by people standing around waiting, we said we'd like to wait for a table. He seemed rather displeased by this and said I don't even remember what your name was on the list. Long story short, we eventually got a table. The server came by and was extremely short with us. We asked for some recommendations and he also seemed displeased that we wanted to get some of his thoughts before immediately placing an order. He said "get the Benedict or the shrimp", briskly took the order, grabbed the menus and left without another word. Up till this point, it was about a one star. But maybe the food would make up the difference? Nope. We got the crawfish beignets to start, which looked delicious, but tasted mediocre. The filling was very tasty, but the outside was far too doughy and didn't absorb any flavors. (3/5) We then decided to order the fried chicken Benedict and the shrimp and grits. Fried chicken Benedict was mediocre. The biscuit below was delicious, but all other seasoning and flavors on the chicken and the rest of the Benedict were completely bland. (2/5) The shrimp and grits was OK, but nothing worth writing home about. A rather small portion of shrimp, including two left over tales that had no actual shrimp in them, made for another underwhelming entree. (2.5/5) At least it wasn't super expensive, but it wasn't cheap either. I've had great restaurants that make up for their poor service in food. But unfortunately, you can't have poor service and poor food.

Words and pictures will not do this place justice; if you ever find yourself trying to find a place that offers great food, great service and leaves you wanting more yet satisfied, go to Brenda's! We got the BFC and the portions were massive. The fried chicken was to the point and the biscuit with the house strawberry jelly was great. We got the Beignet Flight and the special that night which was a Banana Ghirardelli bread drizzled with chocolate. And it was the cherry on top to our already great meal. The beignets were quite size-able portions again and allowed our table of 5 to all share and still have some left. And the bread should be moved to the permanent movie because my, was it amazing! Would recommend Brenda's for a special night of any sort or if you're just trying to get some quality, Southern styled food in SF.

I instantly fell in love with this place. I was so excited to try it I walked a mile for lunch to go. Everyone was eating breakfast foods when we walked in. Since it was 1pm, I can only assume it is because their breakfast is just that good. I couldn't decide so I ordered a few different things: Gumbo - The texture and ingredients were spot on. I loved the sausage and chicken combination and just the right amount of rice in the bowl. I just wish it was a little spicier and had more okra. But that's because I'm from the Midwest and that is how we do it. They did have very good hot sauce to add though. Grillades & Grits - The beef tenderloin really was very tender. The spicy creole gravy was a consistency somewhere between gravy and spaghetti sauce. Which is a compliment to the beef. The eggs were perfectly cooked, and biscuit was to die for. Also be sure to try the strawberry preserves sitting on the table. My friend got the fried chicken which had great flavor and came with fries and a biscuit. I can't wait come back next time I'm in San Fran. And this time save some room for the beignets!

It's worth the wait! I felt the southern charm. The biscuits and beignets were out of this world!

Definitely not your typical brunch place. They have Cajun and southern fixings. Get the grits. Seriously, get the grits. So delicious and cheesy. I ordered the tofu scramble, which was definitely different, a lot of Cajun flavor. The service is very fast, and I'd say it's reasonably priced.

After giving up trying to try this spot my first time in SF (defeated by the intimidatingly long line), I finally got to try Brenda's and it was pretty damn good! This time, we got there around 9am and were seated immediately. We didn't want a heavy meal so we only got two things: shrimp and grits and beignets (crawfish and chocolate). The shrimp and grits were so cheesy and savory. It was a really rich dish that got overwhelming at times. Definitely glad I had my boyfriend to share this with because I wouldn't have been able to eat it myself! The shrimps were juicy and the grits were a great consistency. For the beignets, we chose to get two individuals instead of opting for the flight - good decision, we wouldn't have been able to finish! Chocolate was super rich and sweet. Pretty sure they used dark chocolate, my favorite. The crawfish, though, was worth the hype! We had thick chunks of crawfish in our beignets and it was just incredibly warm and comforting. The exterior of the beignets were a little too fried for me. I'm more used to a softer exterior. But all in all, our meal at Brenda's was one to remember.

Firstly, parking here is a disaster. We drove around for a while until we could find parking outside a Metro PCS, which wasn't too far away. It was around 11:30 am on Thursday. It was quite packed inside but for a party of 2, it only took 15 minutes to get seated. The coffee here was extremely watered down-pass on it next time. The specials chalkboard was filled with mouth watering options. I was quite indecisive but I went with my gut and ordered the pulled pork & sweet potato hash as well as a beignet sampler to share. My sweet potato hash was heavily peppered and overseasoned. I couldn't appreciate the taste of the sweet potatoes. The biscuits were amazingggg~ I've never had such a moist and buttery biscuit. Definitely skip the toast and get the biscuit with your order! The pulled pork was tasty. Might not be worth $13 but I'd give it 3.5 stars. All the beignet flavors were wonderful. It came with chocolate, plain, apple pie, and crawfish. The ones that stood out the most to me were the chocolate filled ones and the crawfish one. The chocolate one had just enough filling so that it wasn't too sweet. The crawfish beignet was savory and the seasonings were perfect. I recommend ordering the crawfish ones! Pork belly with grits was 5 stars. The pork belly was perfectly tender and soft. The poached egg was a perfect touch. The grits were creamy and full of flavor. Service was just ok. They didn't check on us and did not refill any water. This place is on the pricier side. I would still want to come back and try other breakfast items or the shrimp po'boys.

Arrived around 9 am and didn't have to wait too long, maybe 30 minutes? However, a few minutes after we put our name down, the ENTIRE board filled with names so make sure you don't come too late in the morning. The portions are humongous so I ordered 3 things to share amongst 4 people family style. The food came fast after I ordered, so after you sit down you don't need to wait much longer. I ordered the: Crawfish beignet- Doughy pastry filled with globs of cheese and crawfish. When you bite into it the filling oozes out with yummy goodness. It comes with 3 and they're about the size of my palm. Shrimp and grits- Wow. After reading all the Yelp reviews about it I knew I had to get it but I really didn't expect it to be *that* good. But it really was just that good. It was so creamy and cheesy with a decent amount of shrimp. A must get at Brenda's. Banana foster French toast- This was a special so it isn't on the main menu. I doubt most people can finish the amount of toast they give. It wasn't amazing but it still tasted solid. The bananas and whipped cream were a nice touch. Probably one of the nicer French toasts I've had. If you eat at Brenda's be prepared to wait and come on an empty stomach because you will leave very very full.

I visited Brenda's 3 times and here's the summary - what's different from each visit: the food I ordered - what's consistent: I thoroughly enjoyed my food and my dining experience.     Firstly, parking here is a disaster. We drove around for a while until we could find parking outside a Metro PCS, which wasn't too far away. It was around 11:30 am on Thursday. It was quite packed inside but for a party of 2, it only took 15 minutes to get seated.

    The coffee here was extremely watered down-pass on it next time. The specials chalkboard was filled with mouth watering options. I was quite indecisive but I went with my gut and ordered the pulled pork & sweet potato hash as well as a beignet sampler to share. My sweet potato hash was heavily peppered and overseasoned. I couldn't appreciate the taste of the sweet potatoes.

    The biscuits were amazingggg~ I've never had such a moist and buttery biscuit. Definitely skip the toast and get the biscuit with your order!

    The pulled pork was tasty. Might not be worth $13 but I'd give it 3.5 stars.

    All the beignet flavors were wonderful. It came with chocolate, plain, apple pie, and crawfish. The ones that stood out the most to me were the chocolate filled ones and the crawfish one. The chocolate one had just enough filling so that it wasn't too sweet. The crawfish beignet was savory and the seasonings were perfect. I recommend ordering the crawfish ones!

    Pork belly with grits was 5 stars. The pork belly was perfectly tender and soft. The poached egg was a perfect touch. The grits were creamy and full of flavor.

    Service was just ok. They didn't check on us and did not refill any water. This place is on the pricier side. I would still want to come back and try other breakfast items or the shrimp po'boys.

    Arrived around 9 am and didn't have to wait too long, maybe 30 minutes? However, a few minutes after we put our name down, the ENTIRE board filled with names so make sure you don't come too late in the morning.
    The portions are humongous so I ordered 3 things to share amongst 4 people family style. The food came fast after I ordered, so after you sit down you don't need to wait much longer.

    I ordered the:
    Crawfish beignet- Doughy pastry filled with globs of cheese and crawfish. When you bite into it the filling oozes out with yummy goodness. It comes with 3 and they're about the size of my palm.
    Shrimp and grits- Wow. After reading all the Yelp reviews about it I knew I had to get it but I really didn't expect it to be *that* good. But it really was just that good. It was so creamy and cheesy with a decent amount of shrimp. A must get at Brenda's.
    Banana foster French toast- This was a special so it isn't on the main menu. I doubt most people can finish the amount of toast they give. It wasn't amazing but it still tasted solid. The bananas and whipped cream were a nice touch. Probably one of the nicer French toasts I've had.

    If you eat at Brenda's be prepared to wait and come on an empty stomach because you will leave very very full.
